%N A389487 Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of heapable permutations of length n with exactly k increasing runs.
%C A389487 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389487 An increasing run in a permutation is a maximal contiguous subsequence that is increasing.
%C A389487 For example, in the permutation (3,1,4,2) the increasing runs are (3), (1,4), and (2).
